hassle option.  '),(17,6,'It works perfectly.  '),(18,6,'Price was right.'),(19,7,'This remote, for whatever reason, was chosen by Time Warner to replace their previous silver remote, the Time Warner Synergy V RC-U62CP-1.12S.  '),(20,7,'The actual function of this CLIKR-5 is OK, but the ergonomic design sets back remotes by 20 years.  '),(21,7,'The buttons are all the same, there\'s no separation of the number buttons, the volume and channel buttons are the same shape as the other buttons on the remote, and it all adds up to a crappy user experience.  '),(22,7,'Why would TWC accept this as a replacement?  '),(23,7,'This remote is virtually impossible to pick up and use without staring at it to make sure where your fingers are.  '),(24,7,'Heck, you have to feel around just to figure out if you\'ve grabbed it by the top or bottom, since there\'s no articulation in the body of the thing to tell you which end is up.  '),(25,7,'Horrible, just horrible design.  '),(26,7,'I\'m skipping this and paying double for a refurbished Synergy V.'),(27,8,'We had an old Time Warner Cable remote that was dropped into a bucket of dirty mop water.  '),(28,8,'We dried it out and it seemed to work &#34;fine&#34; except for the few times one of the batteries began to sizzle and smoke and became hotter than anything I had ever felt before and literally burned a hole in our couch upholstery.  '),(29,8,'Needless to say, this remote, the CLIKR-5, is awesome, easily programmed, and works perfectly with our TWC equipment and all the other A/V components.  '),(30,8,'I love this remote... great product.  '),(31,8,'(Probably goes without saying, but just in case, you don\'t get the TWC logo on it.)'),(32,9,'This unit works just like the TEC unit only better. '),(33,9,'I like it and would buy another if needed. '),(34,9,'OK?'),(35,10,'It is an exact duplicate of my Time warner remote.I bought it so my wife could control the TV from her chair and not ask me to do it every time.It works great.I would reccomend it to anyone.'),(36,11,'Works on my t.v. that no other remote works on.  '),(37,11,'Was hard as heck to find a compatible one.  '),(38,11,'Even works with my old blu ray player.  '),(39,11,'Doesn\'t work with my old VCR but that thing is so old it would be like walking on water if it did.'),(40,12,'I have owned two Rand McNally GPS devices over the last two years. '),(41,12,'Buyer beware! '),(42,12,'They are pieces of junk. '),(43,12,'The software is great, but the hardware does not last. '),(44,12,'The first GPS lasted a year. '),(45,12,'I spent another $400, that one lasted about 14 months. '),(46,12,'If you don\'t mind spending $400 a year for a GPS buy one. '),(47,12,'Otherwise do not buy it it is the worst and most expensive piece of junk I have ever bought. '),(48,12,'I still use my original GARMIN I purchased in 2006.'),(49,13,'We got this GPS for my husband who is an (OTR) over the road trucker.  '),(50,13,'Very Impressed with the shipping time, it arrived a few days earlier than expected...  '),(51,13,'within a week of use however it started freezing up... could of just been a glitch in that unit.  '),(52,13,'Worked great when it worked!  '),(53,13,'Will work great for the normal person as well but does have the \"trucker\" option. '),(54,13,'(the big truck routes - tells you when a scale is coming up ect...)  '),(55,13,'Love the bigger screen, the ease of use, the ease of putting addresses into memory.  '),(56,13,'Nothing really bad to say about the unit with the exception of it freezing which is probably one in a million and that\'s just my luck.  '),(57,13,'I contacted the seller and within minutes of my email I received a email back with instructions for an exchange! '),(58,13,'VERY impressed all the way around!'),(59,14,'I\'m a professional OTR truck driver, and I bought a TND 700 at a truck stop hoping to make my life easier.  '),(60,14,'Rand McNally, are you listening?'),(61,14,'First thing I did after charging it was connect it to my laptop and install the software and then attempt to update it.  '),(62,14,'The software detected a problem with my update and wanted my home address so I could be sent a patch on an SD card.  '),(63,14,'Hello?  '),(64,14,'I don\'t think I\'m all that unusual; my home address is a PO box that a friend checks weekly and that I might get to check every six months or so.  '),(65,14,'I live in my truck and at truck stops.  '),(66,14,'If you need to make a patch available on an SD card then you should send the SD cards to the truck stops where the devices are sold.  '),(67,14,'I ran the update program multiple times until the program said that the TND 700 was completely updated.I programmed in the height (13\'6\"), the length (53\') and the weight (80,000#) of my rig and told it that I preferred highways.  '),(68,14,'I was parked at a truck stop in the Cincinnati OH area.  '),(69,14,'My next pickup was about 15 miles down the same freeway but on the other side of it a couple of blocks.  '),(70,14,'My cell phone GPS (Sprint) said to get on the freeway to get to my pickup.  '),(71,14,'The TND 700 routed me thru 23 miles of residential streets before finally getting me to my pickup.  '),(72,14,'Very exciting, especially since every time I refused to turn down a street posted \"No Trucks\" the TND 700 took almost 5 minutes to figure a re-route, and it happened multiple times on that short trip.I decided to give it another chance.  '),(73,14,'After my pickup on the north side of Cincinnati just off of I-75 I needed to head to Phoenix AZ via I-71.  '),(74,14,'Easy route is to just hop on I-75 and drive west and south to the intersection of I-71.  '),(75,14,'Indeed, that is what my cell phone advised.  '),(76,14,'The TND 700, however, wanted to route me over surface streets across the city and pick up I-75 on the other side of the city.  '),(77,14,'I turned it off and the next time I passed a truck stop of the same chain I purchased it at I returned it and got my money back.I then spent $30 on a cheap printer.  '),(78,14,'Now I take a minute to set up my route on Google and print it out.  '),(79,14,'Hasn\'t gotten me lost yet over several cross country trips.'),(80,15,'This is a great truck GPS. '),(81,15,'I\'ve tried others and nothing seems to come close to the Rand McNally TND-700.Excellent screen size and resolution. '),(82,15,'The audio is loud enough to be heard over road noise and the purr of my Kenworth/Cat engine. '),(83,15,'I\'ve used it for the last 8,000 miles or so and it has only glitched once. '),(84,15,'Just restarted it and it picked up on my route right where it should have. '),(85,15,'The exit lane screen has been spot on every time and gives me plenty of time to get my rig into the appropriate lane safely. '),(86,15,'I also love the multi-stop route planning and use it a lot. '),(87,15,'Updated regularly, it has shown me all the construction zones and has a feature to allow me to detour around them. '),(88,15,'Creating Groups and storing locations in them is a breeze so I can separate warehouse from store locations, etc.I\'m running an HP Pavilion laptop with Windows 7 OS for the dock and update. '),(89,15,'The USB port DOES charge the GPS, at least with my laptop, despite the warning in a previous review. '),(90,15,'Even if it didn\'t, the supplied 12-volt and AC chargers take care of getting the battery up to speed.My complaints are relatively minor:Battery life when it is unplugged isn\'t great. '),(91,15,'However, since I use it plugged in in the cab 95% of the time, it doesn\'t create too much of a problem.The announcement of state borders coming up is nice but it doesn\'t tell you (or show you on the map display) what state you are in and/or going into. '),(92,15,'Again, a minor issue because I know where I am but all my other GPS units had this feature. '),(93,15,'For $500 smackers, I don\'t expect this kind of slip-up.There is a Micro SD slot on the unit and I bought a card for it. '),(94,15,'Unfortunately, the manual has absolutely no information on using it. '),(95,15,'The only reference is on the page showing the physical features of the unit, showing the position of the slot. '),(96,15,'Annoying.Clean up the minor issues and this unit rates a solid 5.Rand McNally 528881469 7-inch Intelliroute TND 700 Truck GPS'),(97,16,'Well, what can I say.  '),(98,16,'I\'ve had this unit in my truck for about four days now.  '),(99,16,'Prior to that I had a Garmin 755T non-truck GPS.  '),(100,16,'One of my favorite features in that unit was the ability to plan a route by determining mileage using the stop or via feature.  '),(101,16,'What I would do is using a map I would route myself several different ways forcing the unit by putting in stops or vias at different locations along the route, otherwise, like most GPS \'s, it determines what it thinks is the best route.  '),(102,16,'I could add up to 10 Via\'s or stop points for each route and then based on mileage and other factors determine which is the best route to take.  '),(103,16,'Multiple stops and the ability to route was the most important reason for having the Garmin.  '),(104,16,'However it was not truck specific.  '),(105,16,'And considering I am now hauling strictly hazmat I wanted something that would take that into consideration.  '),(106,16,'After perusing various forums, review sites, and word-of-mouth my choices boiled down to the Garmin 465T or the RAND McNally Intelliroute TND 700.  '),(107,16,'Even though it was quite a bit more than the Garmin I chose the TND 700 for several reasons.  '),(108,16,'The main one being the extra screen size, and its ability to coordinate with the RAND McNally truck atlas and also its ease of updating.Now on to my first impression of the TND 700.  '),(109,16,'It seems to be an aesthetically pleasing and durably built unit.  '),(110,16,'The first thing I noticed was it\'s very slow to boot compared to my old Garmin.  '),(111,16,'Whether this is unique to the TND 700 or is common amongst all 